      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(tools): propagate external content provenance to policy hooks",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdds structured external-content provenance to `before_tool_call` hook events and contexts. Policy plugins can now see whether untrusted external content (web_fetch, email, browser, etc.) was present in the model context that led to a tool call.\n\n## What changed\n\n- **New detector** in `src/agents/tool-hook-external-content.ts`: parses production `<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"...\">>>` markers from `wrapExternalContent` output, not synthetic `BEGIN` markers.\n- **New types** in `src/plugins/hook-types.ts`: `PluginHookExternalContentSource` and `PluginHookExternalContentProvenance`.\n- **Hook propagation** in `src/agents/agent-tools.before-tool-call.ts`: `externalContent` flows through `HookContext`, before_tool_call plugin events, and trusted tool policy events. Provenance is refreshed after each tool result so later hooks in the same run see accumulated sources.\n- **Shared hook context** in `src/agents/agent-tools.ts`: `createOpenClawCodingTools` accepts an optional `beforeToolCallHookContext` so callers can share provenance state across wrapped tool instances. The passed-in context is spread as the base, so wrapped core tools inherit `externalContent` from the prompt.\n- **Prompt provenance** in `src/agents/embedded-agent-runner/run/attempt.ts`: initial provenance is detected from the prompt and seeded into the hook context before any tool calls fire.\n- **Docs** in `docs/plugins/hooks.md`: documented the new `externalContent` field and source semantics.\n- **Bug fix**: `structuredClone` in `recordAdjustedParamsForToolCall` now wrapped in try/catch so hostile proxy objects do not break tool execution.\n- **Anti-spoofing fix**: `Source:` labels are only read from the metadata section between the start marker and `---` separator, not from the untrusted content body.\n\n## Why\n\nExternal content is already wrapped as untrusted prompt text by `wrapExternalContent`. Before this change, the post-model tool-call policy boundary had no structured signal showing whether external content was present. Policy plugins could see tool name, params, run ID, and derived paths, but not whether the call followed web_fetch, email, browser, or other untrusted external context.\n\n## Production detector\n\nThe detector recognizes the production `wrapExternalContent` marker format:\n\n```text\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"abc123\">>>\nSource: Web Fetch\n---\nsanitized content\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"abc123\">>>\n```\n\nIt scans any string value, including tool results, prompt text, and hook context fields, for these markers and extracts the `Source:` label from the metadata section only. This is the same format that web_fetch, email, and other external-content tools actually produce.\n\n## Wiring fix (ClawSweeper P1)\n\nPrevious versions seeded prompt provenance into `catalogToolHookContext` only, but `createOpenClawCodingTools` built its own separate hook context for wrapped core tools. The first real tool call, such as exec or read, after an external-content prompt could reach policies without `externalContent`.\n\nFix: `createOpenClawCodingTools` now accepts `beforeToolCallHookContext` which is spread as the base of the internal `hookContext`. `attempt.ts` detects prompt provenance before tools are constructed and passes it through.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: External content provenance must survive a same-run OpenClaw runtime path where a web_fetch-style tool result adds production-wrapped untrusted content and a later `exec` tool call reaches a trusted policy hook with structured `externalContent` provenance.\n- Real environment tested: PR head `75655bc162`, local Linux worktree `/home/rev/projects/openclaw-pr91800`, Node.js v24.15.0.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch: From the PR checkout, ran a `node --import tsx` live runtime command that imported production OpenClaw modules from `src/agents/agent-tools.before-tool-call.ts`, `src/plugins/runtime.ts`, `src/plugins/hook-runner-global.ts`, and `src/security/external-content.ts`; registered an active trusted tool policy; wrapped `web_fetch` and `bash` tools with `wrapToolWithBeforeToolCallHook`; executed `web_fetch` first with production `wrapExternalContent(...)` blocks for `web_fetch` and `email`; then executed `bash` as the follow-up tool call.\n- Evidence after fix (screenshot, recording, terminal capture, console output, redacted runtime log, linked artifact, or copied live output): Copied live stdout from the PR-head command:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"proof\": \"pr-91800 externalContent propagation live runtime capture\",\n  \"node\": \"v24.15.0\",\n  \"cwd\": \"/home/rev/projects/openclaw-pr91800\",\n  \"sharedContextExternalContentAfterFetch\": {\n    \"present\": true,\n    \"sources\": [\n      \"email\",\n      \"web_fetch\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"trustedPolicyCalls\": [\n    {\n      \"event\": {\n        \"toolName\": \"web_fetch\",\n        \"runId\": \"run-fetch-then-exec-live-proof\",\n        \"toolCallId\": \"fetch-1\"\n      },\n      \"ctx\": {\n        \"toolName\": \"web_fetch\",\n        \"runId\": \"run-fetch-then-exec-live-proof\",\n        \"toolCallId\": \"fetch-1\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"event\": {\n        \"toolName\": \"exec\",\n        \"runId\": \"run-fetch-then-exec-live-proof\",\n        \"toolCallId\": \"exec-1\",\n        \"externalContent\": {\n          \"present\": true,\n          \"sources\": [\n            \"email\",\n            \"web_fetch\"\n          ]\n        }\n      },\n      \"ctx\": {\n        \"toolName\": \"exec\",\n        \"runId\": \"run-fetch-then-exec-live-proof\",\n        \"toolCallId\": \"exec-1\",\n        \"externalContent\": {\n          \"present\": true,\n          \"sources\": [\n            \"email\",\n            \"web_fetch\"\n          ]\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n- Observed result after fix: The first `web_fetch` policy event/context had no `externalContent`, then the shared hook context refreshed from the returned production external-content markers to `{\"present\":true,\"sources\":[\"email\",\"web_fetch\"]}`. The later normalized `exec` policy event and policy context both carried that accumulated provenance.\n- What was not tested: Telegram Desktop integration, WhatsApp Web integration, iOS/macOS builds, Windows service install paths, and a paid/model-generated agent turn.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: The live command used the PR checkout's production OpenClaw modules and active plugin registry path, but it avoided network and paid model calls by using deterministic local tool output containing production `wrapExternalContent` blocks. It proves the changed hook/provenance propagation path, not channel UI behavior.\n- Before evidence (optional but encouraged): Before this patch, wrapped tool policy hooks could run without `externalContent` after external prompt/tool content because prompt provenance was seeded into a different hook context and same-run tool-result provenance was not refreshed into the shared policy context.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nFocused regression command run locally:\n\n```bash\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs run --config test/vitest/vitest.e2e.config.ts \\\n  src/agents/agent-tools.before-tool-call.e2e.test.ts \\\n  -t \"refreshes external content provenance after a same-run external tool result\" \\\n  --reporter=verbose\n```\n\nResult:\n\n```text\nTest Files  1 passed (1)\n     Tests  1 passed | 59 skipped (60)\n  Duration  4.83s (transform 2.06s, setup 509ms, import 3.74s, tests 123ms, environment 0ms)\n```\n\nRegression coverage also exercises front-matter `---`, multiple production wrapper blocks, JSON-string rendered tool payloads, and forged `Source: Email` text inside untrusted content bodies.\n",
        "branch": "fix/tool-call-external-provenance",
